TOTAL_PAGES: 1: ​Charles River shareholders reject PETA proposal on monkey research
column7: Shareholders of Charles River Laboratories have overwhelmingly rejected a proposal by the People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals to stop doing business with monkey suppliers that have been accused of violating animal welfare laws.  PETA, a shareholder of Wilmington-based Charles River (CRL), submitted the proposal at the company’s annual meeting on Tuesday.  It asked Charles River to cut ties with suppliers of primates used in drug research that have “repeatedly violated” the federal Animal Welfare Act, which bans the mistreatment of such animals, as well as those under investigation by the U.S. Department of Agriculture.

The U.S. Department of Justice said late Monday that Charles River (CRL) had settled the allegations under the False Claims Act, which bars contractors from defrauding federal programs.  The company hold contracts under which it provides the NIH with mice and other animals for use in lab tests, and maintains colonies of animals.
